## What Is an Antique Cushion Cut Diamond Ring

An antique cushion cut diamond ring is an engagement ring centered on a cushion-shaped diamond cut before approximately 1920 — the period when old mine cutting techniques gave way to modern machine-assisted brillianteering. The old mine cushion cut is the direct ancestor of today's cushion brilliant: both have soft, rounded corners and a roughly rectangular or square outline, but the old mine version was cut entirely by hand, resulting in a higher crown, a smaller table, a larger and more visible culet, and a sparkle pattern built around large, chunky flashes rather than the continuous micro-sparkle of modern cuts.

The confusion in this category comes from how the term "antique cushion cut diamond ring" is used in {{year}} search results and retail listings. Genuine antique cushion rings are estate pieces — recovered from Victorian, Edwardian, or early Art Deco jewelry, often requiring recutting or resetting. Vintage-inspired cushion rings are new rings built on modern vintage-aesthetic settings available from retailers like Blue Nile — these are the practical, accessible version of the antique cushion aesthetic and represent the majority of what buyers in this category actually purchase.

The search intent for "antique cushion cut diamond ring" typically falls into one of two groups: buyers who specifically want a genuine historical piece with provenance and old mine cutting characteristics, and buyers who want the antique aesthetic — milgrain, pavé, Art Deco ornamentation — at a modern retailer's prices with a quality-certified modern cushion. This guide covers both, explains The Old Mine Window (what makes a genuine antique cushion visually distinct), The Estate Premium (what you actually pay for genuine antique origin), and provides the specific settings and builds for buyers choosing the vintage-inspired route at Blue Nile.

