## The Old Mine Window

**The Old Mine Window is the single visual feature that most reliably distinguishes a genuine antique old mine cushion cut from a modern cushion cut — a large, circular opening at the base of the stone (the culet) that appears as a dark or transparent window when viewed face-up from above.** In a modern cushion brilliant, the culet is either absent (pointed) or reduced to a tiny facet invisible without magnification. In an old mine cut, the culet was left large and flat — typically 3–6% of the stone's diameter — creating a visible circle at the center of the stone's table when viewed under any non-directional light source.

The Old Mine Window is not a flaw. It is the signature of handcraft cutting, a visual indicator that the stone was faceted before automated brillianteering techniques standardized crown angles and eliminated the large culet. Buyers who see a circular dark center in a cushion diamond under normal lighting are looking at a genuine old mine cut; buyers who see the even, symmetrical sparkle pattern of a modern cushion with no visible center circle are looking at a post-1920s cut regardless of how the listing describes it.

**Beyond the culet, The Old Mine Window extends as a concept to the entire proportional signature of antique cushion cuts.** Old mine cushions have crown angles 5–10 degrees steeper than modern cushion brilliants, creating a taller profile visible from the side. Their table percentage is smaller — typically 40–55% of girdle diameter versus 60–70% in modern cushion cuts — producing a smaller, more defined table facet surrounded by steep bezel facets; these combined proportions create the chunky, high-domed profile from the side and the distinctive large-flash sparkle that old mine cut collectors specifically seek.

> "Every old mine cushion I examine carries The Old Mine Window in some form — the culet size varies, but the proportional signature of high crown, small table, and hand-cut asymmetry is present in every genuine piece. When a client shows me a stone described as antique and The Old Mine Window isn't there in any form, I know it's a modern cut regardless of the provenance claim. It's the most reliable authentication test available without a grading certificate."
> — Farzana, Diamond Consultant

## The Estate Premium

**The Estate Premium is the price markup applied to genuine antique cushion cut diamonds above what a comparable modern-cut stone with equivalent quality specifications would cost — a premium that reflects rarity, historical provenance, and collector market demand rather than any objective improvement in cut quality or face-up appearance.** A genuine GIA-graded old mine cushion cut in 1ct G-VS1 quality can trade at 30–70% above a modern GIA 1ct G-VS1 cushion brilliant at equivalent specifications, purely due to its antique origin. The Estate Premium is real, measurable, and entirely voluntary — buyers pay it because they want the specific historical aesthetic, not because it improves the ring's visual performance.

The Estate Premium compounds in two ways that buyers often don't account for. First, resale liquidity for genuine antique stones is significantly lower than for modern certified stones — the market of buyers who specifically want a GIA-graded old mine cushion is smaller than the market for modern cushion brilliants, meaning estate pieces can be difficult to sell quickly at purchase price. Second, genuine antique cushion rings in their original settings often require restoration: prong retipping, setting refurbishment, or complete resetting, which adds $500–$2,500 to the true acquisition cost depending on condition.

**The Estate Premium is worth paying when antique origin is a genuine, non-negotiable requirement — a family heirloom tradition, a specific historical era preference, or an Old Mine Window aesthetic that modern cuts cannot replicate.** It is not worth paying for buyers who simply want a ring that looks vintage, because vintage-inspired settings at Blue Nile with a quality modern cushion achieve 90% of the antique aesthetic at 40–60% of the total cost. The specific test: if you cannot distinguish the difference between an old mine cushion and a modern cushion brilliant at normal wearing distance (12–18 inches), the Estate Premium provides you no visual benefit — buy the vintage-inspired modern ring instead.

