## Antique Cushion Cut vs Modern Cushion Cut

The antique cushion cut (old mine) and the modern cushion brilliant are related shapes with fundamentally different optical characters that become visible once you know what to look for. The following comparison covers the key distinguishing features buyers need to evaluate.

<table class="dc-custom-table"><thead><tr><th>Feature</th><th>Old Mine Cushion (Antique)</th><th>Modern Cushion Brilliant</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Crown angle</td><td>38–45° (very steep)</td><td>30–36° (standard brilliant)</td></tr><tr><td>Table size</td><td>40–55% of girdle diameter</td><td>60–70% of girdle diameter</td></tr><tr><td>Culet</td><td>Large, visible (3–6% diameter)</td><td>Absent or microscopic point</td></tr><tr><td>Facet count</td><td>58 (hand-cut, irregular)</td><td>58–64 (precision cut)</td></tr><tr><td>Sparkle pattern</td><td>Large, chunky, slow-moving flashes</td><td>Continuous micro or large-flash pattern</td></tr><tr><td>Silhouette</td><td>Asymmetric, organic pillow</td><td>Symmetric, precise cushion outline</td></tr><tr><td>Profile (side view)</td><td>High-domed, visible pavilion</td><td>Flatter, more consistent depth</td></tr><tr><td>Certification</td><td>GIA, AGS, or ungradeable</td><td>GIA or IGI standard</td></tr><tr><td>Typical price premium</td><td>30–70% above modern equivalent</td><td>Baseline</td></tr><tr><td>Availability</td><td>Estate dealers, auction houses</td><td>Blue Nile, James Allen, major retailers</td></tr></tbody></table>

The silhouette difference is the most accessible visual cue for non-specialists. A genuine old mine cushion viewed from above has slightly irregular corner curvature — no two corners are perfectly matched — because the cutter worked by eye without modern symmetry gauges. A modern cushion has consistent, reproducible corner geometry cut with computer-guided precision — side by side, the old mine reads as organic and imperfect; the modern reads as precise and geometric.

**The sparkle difference is the other key distinction.** Because old mine cushions have steeper crowns and smaller tables, they produce large, well-separated flashes of light rather than the continuous sparkle clouds of modern cuts. In dim or candlelight an old mine cushion outperforms a modern cushion brilliant — the large flash pattern is more visible in low-intensity directional light; in bright overhead lighting the modern cushion produces more consistent and visible sparkle.

## Victorian Cushion Cut Diamond Ring

Victorian-era cushion cut diamond rings (approximately 1837–1901) represent the earliest and purest expression of the old mine cushion aesthetic. Diamond jewelry in the Victorian period centered on yellow gold settings with intricate handcraft milgrain, filigree scrollwork, and often gemstone accents — sapphire, ruby, and emerald were commonly paired with old mine cushion diamonds in both halo and cluster configurations. The cushion's soft, rounded corners suited Victorian design sensibility toward organic, floral motifs rather than the geometric precision that would come later.

Genuine Victorian cushion cut rings in fine condition are among the most expensive antique jewelry categories — a documented Victorian 1ct old mine cushion in original yellow gold setting can command $8,000–$25,000 at specialist auction, depending on stone quality, setting complexity, and provenance documentation. The Estate Premium is at its maximum in the Victorian category because of the combination of extreme age, original metalwork condition, and historical documentation required to establish authenticity.

**Buyers who want the Victorian aesthetic without the Victorian Estate Premium should look at the [Milgrain and Pavé V-Shank Diamond Ring in 14K Yellow Gold at $1,790](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/milgrain-and-pave-v-shank-diamond-engagement-ring-in-14k-yellow-gold-1-8-ct-wt-item-203569?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) (36 reviews) — yellow gold, milgrain detail, and a V-shank profile that echoes Victorian metalwork conventions in a new, certified, warranty-backed ring.** Paired with a cushion modified brilliant in G-H color, this setting creates an authentic period-aesthetic result at a fraction of genuine Victorian acquisition cost. Full context on cushion cut aesthetics in our [Old Mine Cushion Cut Diamond guide](/old-mine-cushion-cut-diamond).

## Edwardian Cushion Cut Diamond Ring

Edwardian cushion cut diamond rings (approximately 1901–1910) mark the transition from Victorian yellow gold to platinum as the dominant setting metal. Edward VII's court favored lighter, more delicate jewelry than the heavy gold of Victoria's reign, and the introduction of platinum allowed jewelers to create intricate filigree, lace-like openwork, and thin milgrain borders that were structurally impossible in gold. Edwardian cushion rings in platinum or platinum-topped gold are among the most technically elaborate pieces of antique jewelry ever made.

The Edwardian aesthetic translated perfectly to cushion cut diamonds because the shape's soft corners and large table complemented the era's preference for stone-forward designs where the metal serves the diamond rather than competing with it. Milgrain borders, ribbon bows, and pierced metalwork were the dominant Edwardian motifs — they frame the cushion's face-up surface while adding substantial visual complexity to the setting without increasing the stone size.

**The modern equivalent of the Edwardian cushion ring is the [Milgrain Lace Pavé Vintage-Style Engagement Ring in 14K White Gold at $2,650](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/milgrain-lace-pave-vintage-style-engagement-ring-in-14k-white-gold-by-james-allen-item-315055?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) (17 reviews) — lace-patterned pavé along the band, milgrain beading at the prong edges, and a white gold construction that reads visually as platinum.** For buyers whose specific aesthetic target is Edwardian milgrain detail without the complexity and cost of a genuine estate piece, this setting delivers the defining visual elements at a predictable price in a new, conditioned ring. See also our [Cushion Cut Diamond Engagement Ring guide](/cushion-cut-diamond-engagement-ring).

