## Art Deco Cushion Cut Diamond Ring

Art Deco cushion cut diamond rings (approximately 1920–1935) represent the period when the cushion shape began its transition toward the modern round brilliant as the dominant diamond cut — making Art Deco pieces the last major era in which cushion cuts anchored the most elaborate fine jewelry designs. Art Deco style brought geometric precision, contrasting colors (onyx, coral, sapphire against diamond), and architectural symmetry to ring design. Art Deco cushion rings are the most graphically bold of the antique cushion categories, with angular channel-set accent stones and stepped geometric metalwork framing the cushion's organic softness.

The visual contrast between the Art Deco setting's geometric structure and the cushion diamond's organic soft corners is one of the most compelling aesthetic tensions in fine jewelry — it is this contrast that makes Art Deco cushion rings so photographically striking. The setting's hard geometry makes the stone's softness more apparent; the stone's warmth makes the setting's precision more deliberate. This is not the case with round brilliants in Art Deco settings, which share the setting's circular geometry rather than contrasting with it.

**The [Art Deco Inspired Fleur-De-Lis Pavé Vintage-Style Engagement Ring in 14K White Gold at $1,190](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/art-deco-inspired-fleur-de-lis-pave-vintage-style-engagement-ring-in-14k-white-gold-by-james-allen-item-315298?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) (102 reviews) is the most accurate Blue Nile rendering of Art Deco cushion ring aesthetics at an accessible price — the fleur-de-lis motif and pavé shoulders directly reference the period's decorative vocabulary without the rarity premium of a genuine 1920s piece.** At 102 reviews, it is one of the most validated vintage-style settings on the platform. Full Art Deco cushion context in our [Cushion Cut Diamond Engagement Ring guide](/cushion-cut-diamond-engagement-ring).

