## Antique Cushion Cut Ring Certification

Certification for antique cushion cut diamond rings falls into two distinct categories that buyers must understand before purchasing. Modern cushion diamonds available from Blue Nile and similar retailers carry GIA or IGI certificates issued on current grading standards — these are reliable, internationally recognized documents that specify cut, color, clarity, and carat weight with consistent methodology. Genuine antique old mine cushion diamonds from estate dealers may or may not carry GIA certification, and the certificate format for old mine cuts differs from modern cushion certificates because GIA cannot apply the same cut grade system to a hand-cut stone with irregular proportions.

A GIA-graded old mine cushion will carry a GIA report number and color/clarity grades but will not carry a "Excellent" cut grade — GIA grades old mine cushions as "Good" cut because the proportions fall outside modern ideal-cut parameters. Buyers should not interpret this "Good" cut grade as a quality deficiency; it is a grading category description, not a quality judgment. The correct evaluation framework for old mine cushion cut quality is The Old Mine Window's proportional profile — crown angle, table percentage, culet size — not modern cut grade standards.

**The certification risk in the antique cushion category is ungradeable stones sold without any laboratory documentation, relying instead on estate appraisals or dealer certificates that carry no independent grading authority.** An estate dealer appraisal that says "1ct G-VS1 old mine cushion" carries significantly less weight than a GIA certificate for the same stone — appraisals are not grading reports and their quality/color assessments are not independently verified. Buyers purchasing genuine antique cushion diamonds above $3,000 should require a GIA report; those without one should budget for an independent GIA grading submission before finalizing the purchase.

> "The certification question is where I see buyers lose the most money in the antique cushion category. A GIA certificate on an old mine cushion costs $150–$300 to obtain and eliminates all uncertainty about the stone's actual quality. Buyers who skip the GIA submission to save time often discover post-purchase that the dealer's color grade was optimistic by one or two grades — and one color grade on a genuine old mine cushion can represent thousands of dollars in value difference."
> — Farzana, Diamond Consultant

