## Antique Cushion Cut vs Old Mine Cut: Are They the Same

Antique cushion cut and old mine cut describe the same type of stone from overlapping historical periods — the confusion arises because the two terms carry different emphasis. "Old mine cut" is the technical term used by gemologists and grading laboratories to describe the specific cutting style of pre-1920s cushion-shaped diamonds: high crown, small table, large culet, hand-cut asymmetric facets. "Antique cushion cut" is the broader market term that encompasses old mine cuts but is also applied to transitional cushion cuts of the 1910s–1930s that bridge old mine and modern brilliant proportions.

The practical distinction matters when buying. A stone specifically labeled "old mine cut" by GIA is a precise technical claim — the stone's proportions fall within the old mine cut parameter range and GIA has confirmed this through grading. A stone labeled "antique cushion cut" by an estate dealer may be a genuine old mine cut, a transitional cut, or a modern cushion in an old-looking setting — the GIA designation is authoritative; the dealer label is marketing.

**For buyers using Blue Nile, "old mine cut" is not available — Blue Nile's inventory is exclusively modern cushion brilliants.** Buyers wanting an old mine cut must use estate dealers, auction houses, or antique diamond specialists. Those wanting the antique aesthetic in a certified modern stone should use Blue Nile's vintage-style settings with cushion modified brilliants — the large-flash pattern comes closest to old mine optical character; see our [Old Mine Cushion Cut Diamond guide](/old-mine-cushion-cut-diamond) for full detail.

